    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey so im doing a lot of hiit lately and my legs feel like they are burning like crazy during the sprints. can u explain what is actually happening with the lactic acid in my muscles when that happens? and how does my body get rid of it after i stop?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That burning sensation during intense sprints is a classic sign of anaerobic metabolism kicking into high gear, which leads to a buildup of hydrogen ions, often associated with lactic acid production. It's not just lactic acid, though; the accumulation of these byproducts is what creates that intense, painful burn in your muscles. When you stop, your body starts clearing this metabolic waste through several mechanisms, primarily the Cori cycle in the liver and oxidation by your mitochondria.",
